</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="35" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="35">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="8" pageNumber="35">
Thirteen species are included in this genus (
<bibRefCitation pageId="8" pageNumber="35">ThripsWiki 2013</bibRefCitation>
), all breeding in the flowers of 
<taxonomicName genus="Fabaceae" lsidName="Fabaceae" pageId="8" pageNumber="35" rank="genus">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
some as pests of cultivated legumes (
<bibRefCitation author="Masumoto, M" journalOrPublisher="Research Bulletin of Plant Protection Japan" pageId="13" pageNumber="40" pagination="25 - 59" title="Key to genera of the subfamily Thripinae (Thysanoptera: Thripidae) associated with Japanese plant quarantine." volume="46" year="2010">Masumoto 2010</bibRefCitation>
). Recently, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Megalurothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megalurothrips distalis" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="distalis">Megalurothrips distalis</taxonomicName>
(Karny) was recorded from Iran (
<bibRefCitation author="Mirab-balou, M" journalOrPublisher="Munis Entomology and Zoology" pageId="13" pageNumber="40" pagination="944 - 952" title="The Megalurothrips genus-group in Iran (Thysanoptera: Thripidae)." volume="6" year="2011 b">Mirab-balou and Chen 2011b</bibRefCitation>
). The members of this genus all have a pair of dorso-apical setae on the first antennal segment, and abdominal tergite VIII with many scattered microtrichia anterior to the spiracles (
<bibRefCitation author="Mound, LA" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="14" pageNumber="41" pagination="27 - 47" title="An illustrated key to the genera of Thripinae (Thysanoptera) from South East Asia." volume="2265" year="2009">Mound and Ng 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
